            <div class=3D"blog-content">
                <p>Soil salinity is the amount of dissolved salt in soil. S=
oil salinity issues occur when soluble salts begin to accumulate in the roo=
t zone. When soluble salts accumulate in the root zone, water and nutrient =
uptake can be inhibited, which is detrimental to crop production, the envir=
onment, and yields.</p>
<p>Some common signs your fields <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/soi=
l-tests-regenerative-agriculture-maximize-spring-planting/">may have a salt=
 problem</a> include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Growth of =E2=80=9Csalt-loving=E2=80=9D plants</li>
<li>Compact soil texture, resulting in ponding or crusting</li>
<li>White crust</li>
<li>Wet soils days after rain</li>
</ul>
<p>Your crops can also display signs of high salinity in the soil, such as =
inhibited germination and emergence, water-stressed plants, and leaf-tip bu=
rn.</p>
<p><strong>When it comes to high salinity levels, your best line of defense=
 is a great plan to avoid salt accumulation by promoting soil health, textu=
re, and structure. </strong>The next best plan is to recognize the signs of=
 rising saline levels and take action. The earlier soil is treated, the gre=
ater its chances for a full recovery.</p>
<p>Saline areas will grow in size if left unmanaged. It=E2=80=99s important=
 to invest in the health of your soil, which starts with your soil microbes=
. Feeding <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/beneficial-microbes-add-va=
lue-for-soil-moisture-extremes/">beneficial microbes</a> a carbon-rich micr=
obial food, like <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/">PhycoTerra</a>, can he=
lp <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/">promote healthy soil</a> structure&n=
bsp;and texture.</p>
<h2>How do soils become saline?</h2>
<p>Soils become saline when water encounters salt in the soil. The water di=
ssolves the salt and brings it up to the root zone and soil surface through=
 capillary action.</p>
<p>When the water evaporates from the surface, a white crust is often left =
behind. Salt can end up in your soil naturally and/or through human impacts=
.</p>
<p><strong>Naturally,</strong> salt can come from physical or chemical weat=
hering. The submergence of soil in seawater can also raise salinity levels,=
 and rising sea levels increase the risk of seepage into areas lying below =
sea level. Lack of rainfall can also create a salt build-up without the rai=
n to flush salt. Additionally, wind in coastal areas can transport salt inl=
and.</p>
<p><strong>Humans</strong> can impact salt levels by using salt-rich irriga=
tion water, poor irrigation practices, or excess water from water logging o=
r irrigation without proper drainage conditions. Excessive irrigation is es=
pecially dangerous in dry climates with heavy soil, as salt cannot be washe=
d away in rainfall. &nbsp;Salt can accumulate on the surface of your soil d=
ue to <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/improve-soil-structure-prevent=
-soil-compaction/">soil compaction</a>.</p>
<h2>How does soil salinity affect crop production?</h2>
<p>High salinity affects a plant=E2=80=99s physiological, biochemical, and =
molecular features, and reduces productivity. Thus, growers will have to in=
crease seed, water, and fertilizer to turn out smaller yields and lower cro=
p yields per unit or input. Impacts include yields at only <a href=3D"https=
://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4336437/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"=
noopener noreferrer nofollow">20% to 50%</a> of record yields.</p>
<p>Crops also produce less biomass with reduced water use and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://phycoterra.com/blog/high-fertilizer-prices-optimize-your-nutrient-inv=
estment/">nutrient efficiency</a>. Soluble salt creates drought stress due =
to limited water uptake, adding stress to plants. Growers will also have le=
ss choice in crops, as high saline levels will force them to default to sal=
t-tolerant crops.</p>
<p>Your crops may also experience changing disease patterns and an increase=
 of vector-borne diseases. Ultimately, extremely saline soils can become in=
fertile for almost any crop.</p>
<h2>What impact does soil salinity have on soil health?</h2>
<p>The higher your soil=E2=80=99s salinity is, the more your soil will suff=
er. Higher than normal salt levels will reduce water infiltration and reten=
tion. You=E2=80=99ll also notice an increased population of salt-tolerant o=
rganisms and a reduction in the population of previously dominant species. =
High salt levels limit water conductance, soil porosity, and aeration.</p>
<p>Dangerously high salinity levels can destroy all vegetation. Dead soil o=
rganisms can=E2=80=99t perform respiration, residue decomposition, nitrific=
ation, and denitrification =E2=80=93 making a bad situation even worse. The=
se types of soils have higher chances of erosion and degradation from wind =
and water.</p>
<p>Depending on the level of your field=E2=80=99s salinity, soil microbes m=
ay be able to help improve your soil=E2=80=99s health, support crop growth,=
 and enhance overall yield potential. If you have inactive or starving soil=
 microbes, they won=E2=80=99t be able to support your soil=E2=80=99s health=
. <strong>Most farms only have</strong><a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/">=
<strong> 25%</strong></a><strong> of their soil microbes working for them. =
</strong></p>
<h2>How do soil microbes help mitigate salt stress?</h2>
<p><a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/articles/put-soil-microbes-to-wor=
k/">Soil microbes</a> include bacteria and fungi inside your soil. They=E2=
=80=99re the secret weapon when it comes to mitigating salt stress.</p>
<p>Salinity-tolerant plant growth promoting bacteria can assist plants in w=
ithstanding saline conditions. These bacteria trigger an osmotic response, =
provide growth hormones and nutrients, and act as a biocontrol agent. Soil =
microbes also promote growth, nutrient uptake, and increase antioxidant act=
ivities during salt stress.</p>
<p>High-saline levels create <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/adding-=
value-across-the-soil-moisture-spectrum/">drought-like conditions</a>, and =
soil microbes help <a href=3D"https://progressivecrop.com/2022/01/soil-micr=
obes-are-key-partners-for-drought-management/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noo=
pener noreferrer nofollow">mitigate abiotic stress</a> by releasing substan=
ces into the soil and around the roots. The microbiome can also protect pla=
nts through stress avoidance and tolerance. This can enable higher crop pro=
duction despite saline conditions. But, helpful bacteria and fungi can only=
 step in to mitigate salt stress if they=E2=80=99re awake. On average, as m=
uch as 75% of microbes in farm soils are =E2=80=9Csleeping=E2=80=9D, i.e., =
dormant, due to starvation.</p>
<h2>How does soil salinity impact soil microbial functions?</h2>
<p>Some <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/beneficial-microbes-add-valu=
e-for-soil-moisture-extremes/">soil microbes</a> can survive in saline cond=
itions and help crops thrive in higher levels of salt. Recent research sugg=
ests <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/understanding-the-microbiome/">=
soil microbes</a>, especially those associated with plant growth, the rhizo=
sphere, and the mycorrhizal network, can support plant nutrition during env=
ironmental stressors.</p>
<p>Keep in mind, to receive the benefits of soil microbes, they need to be =
fed a <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/products/">carbon product applicati=
on</a>.</p>
<p>While some soil microbes can survive in salty soils, it=E2=80=99s better=
 to have healthy levels of saline to support your soil microbiome=E2=80=99s=
 properties, community structure, and function. Increased levels of salt ca=
n lower overall microbial activity due to osmotic stress and toxic ions. It=
 also reduces your soil microbiome=E2=80=99s diversity and overall populati=
on.</p>
<p>On more advanced levels, high salinity can destroy almost all living org=
anisms in the soil.</p>
<p><picture decoding=3D"async" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-12070 size-ful=
l">
<source type=3D"image/webp" data-lazy-srcset=3D"https://phycoterra.com/wp-c=
