<h2>Practices to Help Mitigate High-Salinity Levels</h2>
<p>If you think you have a salt problem, test for Electrical Conductance (E=
C), as salt raises EC levels. If you do have high salinity, find your highe=
st saline areas and make a plan to correct the damage using one or more of =
the methods below.</p>
<h3>Hydro-practices</h3>
<p>Think of hydro-practices as a way to flush your fields and maintain prop=
er drainage.</p>
<p>Good drainage meets leaching requirements in healthy soils. If your soil=
s have a high saline level, minimize leaching requirements as far as possib=
le to prevent raising groundwater and minimize water input to the drainage =
system.</p>
<p>Drainage systems you could consider implementing include:</p>
<ul>
<li>Surface drainage</li>
<li>Subsurface drainage</li>
<li>Mole drainage</li>
<li>Vertical drainage</li>
</ul>
<p>The depth and spacing of your drainage system is based on the soil type =
and economic considerations for your farm.</p>
<p>When it comes to watering best practices, consider drip irrigation, alte=
rnating water resources, moving to rainfed fields, or desalination irrigati=
on water. Experts also recommend fields at risk for high saline levels incr=
ease irrigation water every three to four watering events to flush salt.</p=
>
<h3>Bio-Practices</h3>
<p>Bio-practices for mitigating saline levels include planting practices an=
d using applications like <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/future-of-soil-=
health/">PhycoTerra</a>.</p>
<p>Applying PhycoTerra to your fields wakes up soil microbes and puts them =
to work to <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/maximize-crop-potential-s=
tacking-carbon-products-with-soil-microbial-food/">improve soil structure</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/start-to-finish-feed-soil-mic=
robes/">yield potential</a>. Our proprietary microalgae superfood supports =
<a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/the-importance-of-n-fixation-and-ino=
culation/">inoculants</a>, which can help reduce abiotic stress, and feeds =
growth-promoting bacteria. It also feeds fungi in mycorrhizal networks, whi=
ch can transport nutrients throughout their complex hyphae systems to crops=
 in need. The bacteria and fungi also improve soil structure and texture, c=
reating better drainage to assist in mitigating high saline levels.</p>
<p>Some crops can mitigate saline levels by adding organic or mineral amend=
ments. And, certain chemicals may neutralize sodic soil conditions. <a href=
=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/maximize-crop-potential-stacking-carbon-pro=
ducts-with-soil-microbial-food/">Adding organics</a> can improve soil perme=
ability and the release of carbon dioxide. Compost or other organic soil am=
endments, including <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/manure-compost-s=
oil-microbial-management/">mulching with manure</a> also support soil micro=
bes, which, in turn, support your soil.</p>
<p>When planting, consider using a cheap seed (like barley) in saline areas=
 and then adding alfalfa later to ensure stand and establishment. You could=
 also choose a crop with high saline tolerance, such as legumes. Or, consid=
er returning high salinity areas to <a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/blog/=
4-regenerative-agriculture-practices-increase-soil-health/">perennial cover=
</a>, or diversifying with agroforestry.</p>
<h3>Soil-practices</h3>
<p>Most soils with increased saline levels can benefit from <a href=3D"http=
s://phycoterra.com/blog/small-grain-crop-post-harvest-residue-management-pr=
actice/">reduced tillage</a>, which supports the <a href=3D"https://phycote=
rra.com/blog/articles/how-soil-and-seed-microbiomes-optimize-plan-vigour/">=
soil microbiome</a>.</p>
<p>If salinity has only impacted part of your fields, you can land level to=
 create a more uniform application of water for better leaching =E2=80=93 o=
r you can introduce a new planting procedure, like planting on sloping beds=
 or raised furrows.</p>
<p>In extreme cases, some growers will consider tilling to improve soil per=
meability, including deep plough to loosen soil aggregates. You can also me=
chanically remove salt from your soil=E2=80=99s surface.</p>
<p>Be careful with how much you disrupt your soil. Continuous tillage and h=
eavy machinery passes can increase soil compaction and salinity issues if g=
rowers aren=E2=80=99t careful.</p>
<h2>The Best Way to Manage Soil Salinity is To Monitor, Plan, and Feed Hung=
ry Soil Microbes</h2>
<p>It=E2=80=99s obviously not just your fields, crops, and microorganisms t=
hat are affected by high salinity levels. Working with high salinity fields=
 requires more labor (to fix or mitigate soil and crop issues) and expensiv=
e soil reclamation programs, and results in less return on investment on ap=
plications like fertilizers and potentially less income and food supply.</p=
>
<p>High salinity levels are one of the <a href=3D"https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.=
gov/pmc/articles/PMC7358356/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener noreferrer =
nofollow">most limiting factors</a> of agricultural productivity and food s=
ecurity. There are ways to make the most of your saline soils by <a href=3D=
"https://phycoterra.com/">supporting your soil health</a>, structure, and t=
exture.</p>
<p><strong>Ready to improve your soil structure, yield potential, and put y=
our secret weapon to work? </strong><a href=3D"https://phycoterra.com/conta=
ct/"><strong>Fill out a contact form</strong></a><strong> to learn more abo=
ut our carbon product application. </strong></p>
